of knowledge and history to Black speculative writing and nineteenth-century epistemology, the role of the unconscious in settler colonialism, and early American writing about masturbation, repression, religion, and secularism and their respective influence on morality. The contributors also offer vital new interpretations of major lines of thought in the history of critique—especially those relating to Freud and Foucault—that will be valuable both for scholars of early American studies and for scholars of the humanities and interpretive social sciences more broadly.Contributors. Max Cavitch, Brian Connolly, Matthew Crow, John J. Garcia, Christopher Looby, Michael Meranze, Mark J. Miller, Justine S. Murison, Britt Rusert, Ana Schwartz, Joan W. Scott, Jordan Alexander Stein  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aAmerican literaturey17th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aAmerican literaturey18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aCriticismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aCavitch, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavitch, Max, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConnolly, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrow, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLooby, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeranze, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Mark J., econtributor.4ctb4https: